<section xml:id="right_triangle_trigonometry"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Right Triangle Trigonometry</title>
  <introduction>
    <image xml:id="deviation-introduction" width="100%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=7]
        \node[above,yshift=2] at (0,0) {start};
        \node[above right] at (11.25:1.2) {end};
        \draw[line width=2pt,-stealth] (0,0) -- (11.25:1.2) node[midway,sloped,above] {actual course};
        \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (1.17694233648,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {reference course};
        \draw[dashed] (1.17694233648,0) -- (1.17694233648,0.234108386419) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1] {deviation};
        \draw ([shift=(0:0.3)]0,0) arc (0:11.25:0.3) node[midway,right,xshift=12,yshift=2] {1 House};
        \draw ([shift=(11.25:-0.1)]0,0) pic {waa-top={waacolor}{-78.75}{0.1}};
        \draw (1.17694233648-0.06,0) -- (1.11694233648,0.06) -- (1.17694233648,0.06);\end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      During a voyage, a navigator utilizes a <em>reference course</em>
      <idx>
        <h>reference course</h>
      </idx>—a line connecting the starting point and destination—to monitor their position. When the waʻa (canoe) encounters winds that veer it off course, the navigator mentally plots their position relative to the reference course. To ensure the destination isn't missed, navigators must monitor their deviation from the intended course, involving measurement of the angle of deviation from the reference course (in units of houses) and determining the distance traveled. This section explores the calculation of trigonometric functions using right triangles, enabling us to assess how much the waʻa has strayed from its intended reference course.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Trigonometric Ratios</title>
    <definition xml:id="def_trig-ratios">
        <title>Trigonometric Ratios</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Consider a right triangle with <m>\theta</m> as one of its acute angles. The trigonometric ratios 
      <idx>
        <h>trigonometric functions</h>
        <h>ratios</h>
      </idx> 
      are defined as follows:
    </p>
    <p></p>
    <image xml:id="fig-right-triangle-opp-adj-hyp" width="60%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw (0,0) -- (5,0) node[midway, below] {adjacent};
        \draw(0,0) -- (5,3) node[midway,above,sloped] {hypotenuse};
        \draw(5,0) -- (5,3) node[midway, below,rotate=90] {opposite};
        \draw ([shift=(0:1)]0,0) arc (0:30.9637565321:1) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(\theta\)};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\frac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} },
        \amp \cos\theta\amp =\frac{\mbox{adjacent} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} },
        \amp \tan\theta\amp =\frac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{adjacent} },</mrow>
        <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\frac{\mbox{hypotenuse} }{\mbox{opposite} },
        \amp \sec\theta\amp =\frac{\mbox{hypotenuse} }{\mbox{adjacent} },
        \amp \cot\theta\amp =\frac{\mbox{adjacent} }{\mbox{opposite} }</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A common mnemonic for remembering these relationships is SOHCAHTOA, formed from the first letters of
      <q>
        <em>S</em>ine is
        <em>O</em>pposite over
        <em>H</em>ypotenuse,
        <em>C</em>osine is
        <em>A</em>djacent over
        <em>H</em>ypotenuse,
        <em>T</em>angent is
        <em>O</em>pposite over
        <em>A</em>djacent.
      </q>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Based on the definition of the six trigonometric functions, we have the following trigonometric identities.
    </p>
      <definition xml:id="def_reciprocal-identities">
        <title>Reciprocal Identities</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <idx>
              <h>reciprocal identities</h>
            </idx>
            <md>
              <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\csc\theta}, \amp  \cos\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\sec\theta}, \amp  \tan\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\cot\theta},</mrow>
              <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\sin\theta}, \amp  \sec\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\cos\theta}, \amp  \cot\theta\amp =\dfrac{1}{\tan\theta}</mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def_quotient-identities">
      <title>Quotient Identities</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>quotient identities</h>
          </idx>
          <md>
            <mrow>\tan\theta \amp =\dfrac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}, \amp  \cot\theta\amp =\dfrac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact values of the six trigonometric ratios of the angle <m>\theta</m> in the given triangle.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="ex-trig-ratios1" width="60%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25]
            \draw (0,0) -- (4,0) node[midway, below] {4};
            \draw(0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,above left] {5};
            \draw(4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway, right] {3};
            \draw ([shift=(0:0.5cm)]0,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.5cm) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(\theta\)};
            \draw (3.6,0) -- (3.6,0.4) -- (4,0.4);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          By the definition of the trigonometric ratios, we have
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\frac{3}{5}, \amp \cos\theta\amp =\frac{4}{5}, \amp \tan\theta\amp =\frac{3}{4},</mrow>
            <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\frac{5}{3}, \amp \sec\theta\amp =\frac{5}{4}, \amp \cot\theta\amp =\frac{4}{3}</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact values of the six trigonometric ratios of the angle
          <m>\theta</m>
          in the given triangle.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="ex-trig-ratios2" width="60%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.25]
            \draw (0,0) -- (5,0) node[midway, below] {5};
            \draw(0,0) -- (5,2);
            \draw(5,0) -- (5,2) node[midway, right] {2};
            \draw ([shift=(201.801409486:0.5cm)]5,2) arc (201.801409486:270:0.5cm) node[midway,left,yshift=-0.1cm] {\(\theta\)};
            \draw (4.6,0) -- (4.6,0.4) -- (5,0.4);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Notice that <m>\theta</m> is in a different position. Here, the adjacent side is three and the opposite side is five. If we let <m>h</m> denote the hypotenuse, then we can use the Pythagorean Theorem to get
          <me>
            h=\sqrt{5^2+2^2}=\sqrt{29}
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then by the definition of the trigonometric ratios, we have
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\frac{5}{\sqrt{29}}, \amp \cos\theta\amp =\frac{2}{\sqrt{29}}, \amp \tan\theta\amp =\frac{5}{2},</mrow>
            <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\frac{\sqrt{29}}{5}, \amp \sec\theta\amp =\frac{\sqrt{29}}{2}, \amp \cot\theta\amp =\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
