  <subsection >
    <title>Cofunctions</title>
    <p>
      <idx>
        <h>cofunctions</h>
      </idx>
      The symmetry between <m>\sin\theta</m> and <m>\cos\theta</m>  becomes evident when reversing the order of sine and cosine values from <m>90^{\circ}</m> to <m>0^{\circ}</m>. This symmetry yields
      <m>\sin0^{\circ}=\cos90^{\circ}</m>,
      <m>\sin30^{\circ}=\cos60^{\circ}</m>,
      <m>\sin45^{\circ}=\cos45^{\circ}</m>,
      <m>\sin60^{\circ}=\cos30^{\circ}</m>,
      and
      <m>\sin90^{\circ}=\cos0^{\circ}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This pattern between sine and cosine is no coincidence; it emerges because the three angles in a triangle add up to <m>180^{\circ}</m> or <m>\pi</m> radians. When considering a right triangle, the remaining two angles combine to form <m>90^{\circ}</m> or <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> radians, making them <em>complementary angles</em>.
      <idx>
        <h>complementary angles</h>
      </idx>
    </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-cofunction" width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
        \draw (0,0) -- (4,0) node[midway,below]{\(b\)};
        \draw(0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,above left]{\(c\)};
        \draw(4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right]{\(a\)};
        \draw(3.7,0) -- (3.7,0.3) -- (4,0.3);
        \draw ([shift=(0:0.5)]0,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.5cm) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(\alpha\)};
        \draw ([shift=({180+atan(3/4)}:0.5)]4,3) arc (216.869897646:270:0.5) node[midway,below,xshift=-0.1] {\(\beta\)};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      Consider the right triangle in the figure above, where angles <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are complementary angles. Side <m>a</m> is opposite of angle <m>\alpha</m>, and side <m>b</m> is opposite of angle <m>\beta</m>.  Notice that we can also describe side <m>b</m> as adjacent to angle <m>\alpha</m> and side <m>a</m> as adjacent to angle <m>\beta</m>. Therefore,
      <me>
        \sin\alpha=\dfrac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\dfrac{a}{c}\mbox{~and~} \cos\beta=\dfrac{\mbox{adjacent} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\dfrac{a}{c}
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus we can conclude that
      <me>
        \sin\alpha=\frac{a}{c}=\cos\beta
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sine and cosine are called
      <term>cofunctions</term>
      <idx>
        <h>cofunctions</h>
      </idx>
      because of this relationship between these functions and their complementary angles. We can obtain similar relationships for all trigonometric functions:
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin\alpha=\frac{a}{c}\amp =\cos\beta, \amp  \cos\alpha=\frac{b}{c}\amp =\sin\beta, \amp  \tan\alpha=\frac{a}{b}\amp =\cot\beta,</mrow>
        <mrow>\csc\alpha=\frac{c}{a}\amp =\sec\beta, \amp  \sec\alpha=\frac{c}{b}\amp =\csc\beta, \amp  \cot\alpha=\frac{b}{a}\amp =\tan\beta</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are complementary angles, <m>\alpha+\beta=90^{\circ}</m>. Rearranging, we get <m>\beta=90^{\circ}-\alpha</m>. Substituting this into our cofunctions and replacing <m>\alpha</m> with <m>\theta</m>, we get our <term>cofunction identities</term>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def_cofunction-identities"><title>Cofunction Identities</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      The cofunction identities 
      <idx>
        <h>cofunction identities</h>
      </idx>
      in degrees are
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\cos(90^{\circ}-\theta), \amp  \cos\theta\amp =\sin(90^{\circ}-\theta), \amp  \tan\theta\amp =\cot(90^{\circ}-\theta),</mrow>
        <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\sec(90^{\circ}-\theta), \amp  \sec\theta\amp =\csc(90^{\circ}-\theta), \amp  \cot\theta\amp =\tan(90^{\circ}-\theta)</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The cofunction identities in radians are
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp  \cos\theta\amp =\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp  \tan\theta\amp =\cot\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right),</mrow>
        <mrow>\csc\theta\amp =\sec\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp  \sec\theta\amp =\csc\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right), \amp  \cot\theta\amp =\tan\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Cofunction Identities explain the symmetry in <xref ref="tab_basic-trig-Q1">Table</xref>.
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin0^{\circ}\amp =\cos(90^{\circ}-0^{\circ})=\cos90^{\circ},\amp \sin30^{\circ}\amp =\cos(90^{\circ}-30^{\circ})=\cos60^{\circ},</mrow>
            <mrow>\sin45^{\circ}\amp =\cos(90^{\circ}-45^{\circ})=\cos45^{\circ},\amp \sin60^{\circ}\amp =\cos(90^{\circ}-60^{\circ})=\cos30^{\circ},</mrow>
            <mrow>\sin90^{\circ}\amp=\cos(90^{\circ}-90^{\circ})=\cos0^{\circ}</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
