  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Right Triangles</title>
    <image xml:id="solving-rt-triangle" width="60%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
        \draw (0,0) -- (4,0) node[midway,below]{\(b\)};
        \draw(0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,above left]{\(c\)};
        \draw(4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right]{\(a\)};
        \draw(3.7,0) -- (3.7,0.3) -- (4,0.3);
        \draw ([shift=(0:0.5cm)]0,0) arc (0:36.8698976458:0.5cm) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(\alpha\)};
        \draw ([shift=(216.869897646:0.5cm)]4,3) arc (216.86989:270:0.5cm) node[midway,below,xshift=-0.1cm] {\(\beta\)};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      Consider the following right triangle where side <m>a</m> is opposite angle <m>\alpha</m>, side <m>b</m> is opposite angle <m>\beta</m>, and side <m>c</m> is the hypotenuse. Since <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are complementary angles, we have
      <me>
        \alpha+\beta=90^{\circ}
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Additionally, by the Pythagorean Theorem, we have
      <me>
        a^2+b^2=c^2
      </me>.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          To <term>solve a triangle</term>
          <idx>
            <h>triangles</h>
            <h>solving</h>
          </idx>
          is the process of determining the values for all three lengths of its sides and the measures of all three angles, based on provided information about the triangle.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <title>Solving Right Triangles</title>
      <p>
        In solving a right triangle, the following relationships are useful:
        <me>
          \alpha+\beta=90^{\circ}, \qquad a^2+b^2=c^2
        </me>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the right triangle. Round your answer to two decimal places.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="solving-rt-triangle-ex" width="50%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.3]
            \draw (0,0) -- (16,0) node[midway,below]{\(16\)};
            \draw(0,0) -- (16,19.0680574815) node[midway,above left]{\(c\)};
            \draw(16,0) -- (16,19.0680574815) node[midway,right]{\(a\)};
            \draw(14.5,0) -- (14.5,1.5) -- (16,1.5);
            \draw ([shift=(0:3)]0,0) arc (0:50:3) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm,yshift=0.1cm] {\(50^{\circ}\)};
            \draw ([shift=(230:3)]16,19.0680574815) arc (230:270:3) node[midway,below,xshift=-0.1cm] {\(\beta\)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Given that this is a right triangle, we already know one angle is <m>90^{\circ}</m>, and we have an additional angle of <m>50^{\circ}</m> along with an adjacent side length of 16. To solve this triangle, we need to determine the values of sides <m>a</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>\beta</m>. We begin by finding the measure of angle <m>\beta</m>. Since <m>50^{\circ}+\beta=90^{\circ}</m> we have
          <me>
            \beta=90^{\circ}-50^{\circ}=40^{\circ}
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Next, we will solve for side <m>a</m>. Using the angle <m>50^{\circ}</m>, where the adjacent side is 16 and side <m>a</m> is the side opposite to the angle, we can apply the tangent function, which  relates the opposite and adjacent sides:
          <me>
            \tan50^{\circ}=\frac{a}{16}
          </me>.
          Multiplying both sides by 16 we get
          <me>
            a=16\cdot\tan50^{\circ}\approx19.07
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Using the Pythagorean Theorem, we get
          <me>
            c^2=16^2+19.07^2\approx619.66
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus
          <me>
            c\approx\sqrt{619.66}\approx24.89
          </me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec_applied-right-triangles">
    <title>Solving Applied Problems</title>
    <example xml:id="ex-deviation">
      <title>Deviation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We are now ready to calculate the deviation example proposed at the start of this section. In an average day of sailing, a waʻa sails 120 nautical miles (NM). If Hikianalia is supposed to sail in the direction of Hikina (East), but currents have deviated her course by one house so she actually sailed in the house Lā, how far off the course has Hikianalia deviated?
        </p>
        <p></p>
        <image xml:id="deviation-example" width="100%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=7]
            \node[above,yshift=2] at (0,0) {start};
            \node[above right] at (11.25:1.2) {end};
            \draw[line width=2pt,-stealth] (0,0) -- (11.25:1.2) node[midway,sloped,above] {actual course};
            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (1.17694233648,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {reference course};
            \draw[dashed] (1.17694233648,0) -- (1.17694233648,0.234108386419) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1] {deviation};
            \draw ([shift=(0:0.3)]0,0) arc (0:11.25:0.3) node[midway,right,xshift=12,yshift=2] {1 House};
            \draw ([shift=(11.25:-0.1)]0,0) pic {waa-top={waacolor}{-78.75}{0.1}};
            \draw (1.17694233648-0.06,0) -- (1.11694233648,0.06) -- (1.17694233648,0.06);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          From the Star Compass (<xref ref="star-compass-32-compass-rose">Figure</xref>), the house Lā is one house (<m>11.25^{\circ}</m>) from Hikina. If we let <m>y</m> denote the distance deviated from the reference course, our right triangle becomes:
        </p>
        <p></p>
        <image xml:id="deviation-example-soln" width="100%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=7]
            \node[above,yshift=0.15cm] at (0,0) {start};
            \node[above right] at (11.25:1.2) {end};
            \draw[line width=2pt,-stealth] (0,0) -- (11.25:1.2cm) node[midway,sloped,above] {120 NM};
            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (1.17694233648,0);
            \draw[dashed] (1.17694233648,0) -- (1.17694233648,0.234108386419)
            node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(y\)};
            \draw ([shift=(0:0.2cm)]0,0) arc (0:11.25:0.2cm) node[midway,right,xshift=0.5cm,yshift=0.07cm] {\(11.25^{\circ}\)};
            \draw ([shift=(11.25:-0.1cm)]0,0) pic {waa-top={waacolor}{(-90+11.25)}{0.1}};
            \draw (1.10694233648,0) -- (1.10694233648,0.07) -- (1.17694233648,0.07);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          Since we know the hypotenuse of the triangle and want to find the side opposite of the angle,
          we will use the sine function:
          <me>
            \sin11.25^{\circ}=\frac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\frac{y}{120\mbox{ NM} }
          </me>;
          multiplying both sides by 120, we get
          <me>
            y=120\cdot\sin11.25^{\circ}\mbox{ NM} \approx23.4\mbox{ NM}
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          So Hikianalia has deviated 23.4 nautical miles north from the reference course.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Solar panels</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solar panels harness the sun's energy to generate electricity, and for optimal energy output, they should be oriented perpendicularly to the sun's light. The sun's angle of elevation varies based on latitude, and in Hawai‘i, for instance, south-facing solar panels are recommended to have a pitch of <m>21^{\circ}</m> to align with the sun's rays. When installing a solar panel, determining its pitch might pose challenges. Instead of measuring the angle directly, an alternative approach involves measuring the height of the panel's top. What height should a south-facing solar panel, measuring 65 inches in length, be installed at to achieve the desired angle of <m>21^{\circ}</m>? Round your answer to the nearest tenth of an inch.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-solar" width="70%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[line width=2pt,red] (0,0) -- (159:6.5) node[black,sloped,midway,below] {Solar Panel};
            \draw (-6.5,0) -- (1,0);
            \draw[dashed] (-6.06827277223,0) -- (-6.06827277223,2.32939167204) node[sloped,midway,above] {Height};
            \draw[stealth-,line width=2pt,yellow] (159:6.5) -- ([shift=(159:6.5)]69:3);
            \draw[stealth-,line width=2pt,yellow] (159:4.875) -- ([shift=(159:4.875)]69:3);
            \draw[stealth-,line width=2pt,yellow] (159:3.25) -- ([shift=(159:3.25)]69:3) node[above,rotate=-21,black] {Sun's rays};
            \draw[stealth-,line width=2pt,yellow] (159:1.625) -- ([shift=(159:1.625)]69:3);
            \draw[stealth-,line width=2pt,yellow] (0,0) -- (69:3);
            \draw (69:0.4) -- ([shift=(159:0.4)]69:0.4) -- (159:0.4);
            \draw ([shift=(0:0.75)]0,0) arc (0:69:0.75) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1cm,yshift=0.3cm,text width=1.9cm,align=left] {Angle of elevation of Sun};
            \draw ([shift=(159:0.75)]0,0) arc (159:180:0.75) node[midway,right,xshift=-1.2cm,yshift=-0.5cm,text width=3cm,align=left] {Pitch angle};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We begin by drawing the triangle.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-solar-soln" width="70%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (159:6.5) node[sloped,midway,above] {65 in};
            \draw (-6.06827277223,0) -- (0,0);
            \draw[dashed] (-6.06827277223,0) -- (-6.06827277223,2.32939167204) node[sloped,midway,above] {Height};
            \draw ([shift=(159:0.75)]0,0) arc (159:180:0.75) node[midway,left,xshift=-0.3cm,yshift=0.1cm] {\(21^{\circ}\)};
            \draw (-6.06827277223,0.4) -- (-5.66827277223,0.4) -- (-5.66827277223,0);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          Since we know the desired angle of pitch of the solar panel and the length of the panel, we can set up the following equation
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin21^{\circ} =\amp \frac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\frac{\mbox{height} }{65\mbox{ in} };</mrow>
            <mrow>\mbox{height} =\amp 65\mbox{ in} \cdot\sin21^{\circ}\approx23.3\mbox{ in}</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus, when installing a solar panel in Hawai‘i, the top of the solar panel should be positioned 23.3 inches above the bottom to optimize energy output.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
