    <exercise>
      <title>Movement of Sand</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The movement of sand on a beach is a dynamic process influenced by various factors, such as waves. When waves approach the shore at an angle, they lead to the shifting of sand. During the <em>swash</em>
          <idx>
            <h>swash</h>
          </idx> phase, as the wave crashes onto the shore, water and sediment move onto the beach following the wave's angle. Subsequently, gravity propels the water and sediment back into the ocean, perpendicular to the shoreline, in a process known as <em>backwash</em>.
          <idx>
            <h>backwash</h>
          </idx> This interplay of swash and backwash creates a zig-zag pattern called <em>longshore drift</em>.
          <idx>
            <h>longshore drift</h>
          </idx>
        </p>
        <p>
          Certain beaches undergo seasonal changes in wave direction. Some experience waves from one direction in one season and from another direction in the next, while those receiving waves predominantly from a single direction might accumulate sand in specific areas.
        </p>
